               <p>THOMAS HURST. I am a <rs id="t18340904-226-viclabel1270" type="occupation">silk manufacturer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-226-victim1343 t18340904-226-viclabel1270"></join>. The prisoner has been my <rs id="t18340904-226-deflabel1271" type="occupation">apprentice</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-226-defend1342 t18340904-226-deflabel1271"></join> three years and a half - on the 28th of August, I and my wife went to bed in the first floor front room - the prisoner slept in the attic - I had ten sovereign and a half - in my trowsers pocket, which I put by the side of the bed - in the morning I got up, and missed a sovereign and a half - I told the prisoner I suspected him- he denied all knowledge of it - I sent for a policeman - I said, "You will not tell me where my money is; I dare say, you will tell the policeman" - they then went into the yard - the policeman afterwards showed me a sovereign, a shilling, and two sixpences - I asked the prisoner how he got it - he said, "I got up at four o'clock in the morning, and took your money, and then went to bed again" - my bed-room door was shut, but not locked.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-226-person1344">
                  JOSEPH 
                  WORMALD
               <interp inst="t18340904-226-person1344" type="surname" value="WORMALD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-226-person1344" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-226-person1344" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a policeman. I took the prisoner - I went into the yard with him, down into the cellar - he went down on his knees, and began searching for the money - I helped him, and found this money concealed under the dirt in the cellar - he picked up a sovereign; I found the silver - he said he went down at four o'clock in the morning, opened his master's door, and took the money out of his purse, in his pocket, and then went to bed - he said his mother told him to take all the money, for she had no tea nor sugar.</p>
